ious\n+\n+## Proposed fix\n+\n+Treat `message_id` collisions with non-identical envelopes as a security event:\n+\n+- compare full envelope bytes or a stable envelope hash before deduplicating\n+- if copies differ, preserve all variants or mark the message as conflicted\n+- prefer a copy only after successful decryption / signature verification\n+- log or surface relay divergence for diagnostics\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- two envelopes with the same `message_id` but different bytes are not silently collapsed\n+- fetch aggregation preserves enough information for the client to recover a valid copy\n+- add tests for conflicting relay responses on both `HttpTransport` and `TransportPool<HttpTarget>`\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/03-replication-authn-and-pin-verification-fail-open.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Node-to-node replication is still fail-open in places where the codebase already advertises stronger guarantees. Peer configs can carry `cert_pin` and `node_pubkey`, but replication does not enforce either one. Signed-header destination verification is also optional and disabled by default.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+This is production-surface security, not future transport work:\n+\n+- replication is already part of current v0.3 behavior\n+- the whitepaper already claims HTTP transport with TLS / certificate pinning\n+- the code currently warns about insecure mode but proceeds anyway\n+\n+That leaves current replication traffic more vulnerable to misrouting / MITM than the rest of the design suggests.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `crates/reme-config/src/validation.rs:131` includes `cert_pin`\n+- `crates/reme-config/src/validation.rs:135` includes `node_pubkey`\n+- `apps/node/src/replication.rs:31` builds a generic `reqwest::Client`\n+- `apps/node/src/replication.rs:137` leaves certificate pinning as TODO\n+- `apps/node/src/replication.rs:142` leaves peer identity verification as TODO\n+- `apps/node/src/config.rs:478` defaults `public_host` to `None`\n+- `apps/node/src/main.rs:160` only warns when destination verification is disabled\n+- `apps/node/src/signed_headers.rs:163` documents `public_host = None` as insecure mode\n+- `apps/node/src/signed_headers.rs:293` skips destination verification when `public_host` is absent\n+- `WHITEPAPER.md:859` says v0.3 transport includes TLS / certificate pinning\n+\n+## Failure mode\n+\n+- a pinned peer is configured but the replication client ignores the pin\n+- a known peer public key is configured but responses are not verified against it\n+- operators can run signed replication with destination binding effectively disabled\n+\n+## Proposed fix\n+\n+- wire per-peer certificate pinning into the replication client\n+- use configured `node_pubkey` to verify peer identity where applicable\n+- tighten startup / validation so identity-enabled replication without `public_host` is not silently accepted\n+- make insecure replication modes explicit opt-in, not implicit defaults\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- configured `cert_pin` is enforced on replication requests\n+- configured `node_pubkey` is used for peer verification or the config rejects unsupported combinations\n+- identity-enabled replication no longer defaults to insecure destination verification\n+- startup / tests make the secure-vs-insecure mode boundary explicit\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/04-fetch-response-size-and-batch-shape-enable-dos.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Mailbox fetch currently returns the entire mailbox as one base64-encoded JSON payload list. Given the current per-mailbox capacity and body-size limits, a hot mailbox can force large allocations and expensive encode/decode work on both node and client.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+This is a present-day availability issue on the current HTTP transport. It does not depend on future BLE / LoRa work.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `apps/node/src/api.rs:53` sets `MAX_BODY_SIZE = 256 * 1024`\n+- `crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs:37` defaults `max_messages_per