messages once\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add HTTP client tests for multi-page retrieval**\n  \n  Needed cases:\n  - `HttpTransport::fetch_once()` follows multiple pages from one node\n  - `HttpTarget::fetch_messages()` does the same\n  - malformed or missing `next_cursor` with `has_more=true` is treated as server error\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run targeted tests and verify they fail**\n  \n  Runs:\n  - `cargo test -p reme-node-core fetch`\n  - `cargo test -p node fetch`\n  - `cargo test -p reme-transport http`\n\n---\n\n## Chunk 2: Mailbox Store Pagination\n\n### Task 3: Add paginated mailbox-store primitives\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: [crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Introduce a paginated fetch result type**\n  \n  Proposed shape:\n  ```rust\n  pub struct FetchPage {\n      pub envelopes: Vec<OuterEnvelope>,\n      pub next_cursor: Option<i64>,\n      pub has_more: bool,\n  }\n  ```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Add a bounded fetch method to the store trait**\n  \n  Proposed API:\n  ```rust\n  fn fetch_page(\n      &self,\n      routing_key: &RoutingKey,\n      limit: usize,\n      after: Option<i64>,\n  ) -> Result<FetchPage, NodeError>;\n  ```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Keep existing `fetch()` as a compatibility wrapper temporarily**\n  \n  It should call `fetch_page()` in a loop so current non-HTTP callers keep compiling during migration.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Implement SQL paging**\n  \n  Required properties:\n  - expired rows filtered out\n  - oldest-first ordering\n  - stable ordering: `ORDER BY created_at ASC, id ASC`\n  - cursor predicate based on mailbox `id`\n  - fetch `limit + 1` rows to compute `has_more`\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Preserve malformed-row cleanup**\n  \n  Existing behavior from `#65` must remain:\n  - deserialize row\n  - collect invalid row ids\n  - delete invalid rows in bounded chunks\n  - only valid envelopes count toward the returned page\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Run mailbox-store tests**\n  \n  Run: `cargo test -p reme-node-core mailbox_store`\n\n- [ ] **Step 7: Commit**\n  \n  ```bash\n  git add crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs\n  git commit -m \"feat: add paginated mailbox fetch\"\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## Chunk 3: Node API Pagination\n\n### Task 4: Expose paginated fetch over HTTP\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: [apps/node/src/api.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/node/src/api.rs)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Add query parsing type**\n  \n  Proposed:\n  ```rust\n  #[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]\n  struct FetchQuery {\n      limit: Option<usize>,\n      after: Option<i64>,\n  }\n  ```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Add server-side fetch batch limit constant**\n  \n  Recommendation:\n  - a separate constant for fetch response batching\n  - not tied to request-body size\n  - start conservative, e.g. `100` envelopes max per page\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Clamp requested `limit`**\n  \n  Behavior:\n  - missing `limit` => server default\n  - `limit == 0` => `400`\n  - `limit > server_max` => clamp to `server_max`\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Update `FetchResponse`**\n  \n  Proposed:\n  ```rust\n  pub struct FetchResponse {\n      pub payloads: Vec<String>,\n      pub next_cursor: Option<String>,\n      pub has_more: bool,\n  }\n  ```\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Call `state.store.fetch_page(...)` instead of `fetch(...)`**\n  \n  Convert `next_cursor` to string for JSON transport.\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Ensure response construction remains bounded**\n  \n  The page limit must bound:\n  - envelope serialization count\n  - base64 encode count\n  - JSON payload count\n\n- [ ] **Step 7: Run targeted API tests**\n  \n  Run: `cargo test -p node fetch`\n\n- [ ] **Step 8: Commit**\n  \n  ```bash\n  git add apps/node/src/api.rs\n  git commit -m \"feat: paginate mailbox fetch API\"\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## Chunk 4: HTTP Client Pagination\n\n### Task 5: Update `HttpTransport` to drain paginated fetches\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: [crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Extend local `FetchResponse` deserialization**\n  \n  Add:\n  - `next_cursor: Option<String>`\n  - `has_more: bool`\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Refactor single-request fetch into page loop**\n  \n  Suggested helper split:\n  - `fetch_page_from_node(...)`\n  - loop in `fetch_from_node(...)`\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add loop guards**\n  \n  Required protections:\n  - break when `has_more == false`\n  - error if `has_more == true` but `next_cursor` missing\n  - optionally detect non-advancing cursor to avoid infinite loops\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Keep aggregation bounded per page**\n  \n  Only one page should be decoded at a time before aggregation.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Preserve current multi-node dedup behavior unless intentionally changed by `#71`**\n  \n  Do not mix `#67` with `#71` conflict-preservation changes.\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Run targeted tests**\n  \n  Run: `cargo test -p reme-transport http::tests::`\n\n### Task 6: Update `HttpTarget` to drain paginated fetches\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: [crates/reme-transport/src/http_target.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/http_target.rs)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Mirror the `FetchResponse` changes**\n- [ ] **Step 2: Add the same page-following logic**\n- [ ] **Step 3: Reuse the same loop safety rules**\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run targeted tests**\n  \n  Run: `cargo test -p reme-transport http_target`\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n  \n  ```bash\n  git add crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs crates/reme-transport/src/http_target.rs\n  git commit -m \"feat: follow paginated mailbox fetch responses\"\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## Chunk 5: End-to-End and Regression Coverage\n\n### Task 7: Add end-to-end coverage for large mailbox retrieval\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: [crates/reme-core/tests/integration.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-core/tests/integration.rs)\n- Possibly modify: [apps/node/tests/](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/node/tests) if a node-specific integration seam is better\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write an integration test that enqueues more than one fetch page**\n  \n  Target behavior:\n  - mailbox contains `server_page_limit + k` messages\n  - client drains them over repeated paginated requests\n  - all messages are retrieved\n  - no single response contains more than configured page size\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Add a regression test for oldest-first draining**\n  \n  Assertions:\n  - first retrieved page contains oldest enqueued messages\n  - later pages contain newer messages\n  - local processing order reduces gap churn compared with newest-first\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add a regression test for continuation correctness with tombstoning**\n  \n  Verify:\n  - client can process page 1\n  - tombstone/delete some messages\n  - continue with cursor and still drain remaining mailbox correctly\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run the focused integration tests**\n  \n  Run: `cargo test -p reme-core --test integration`\n\n---\n\n## Chunk 6: Verification and Handoff\n\n### Task 8: Full verification\n\n**Files:**\n- No code changes expected\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Run format check**\n  \n  `cargo fmt --all -- --check`\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run strict clippy**\n  \n  `cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings`\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Run full test suite**\n  \n  `cargo test --workspace`\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Review diff for accidental API churn**\n  \n  Check especially:\n  - no unrelated transport behavior changes\n  - no change to embedded-node fetch unless intentional\n  - no contamination from PR `#70` branch\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Final commit if verification required fixes**\n  \n  ```bash\n  git add <files>\n  git commit -m \"test: cover paginated mailbox fetch end to end\"\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## Open Decisions Locked For Implementation\n\n- Pagination should be real cursor pagination, not `has_more`-only windowing.\n- Ordering should be oldest-first.\n- Cursor should be based on server-owned mailbox row identity / insertion order, not sender timestamps.\n- Node should clamp fetch page size server-side even if the client requests more.\n- `#67` should stay focused on bounded fetch growth. Do not mix in `#71` dedup redesign unless required for compilation.\n\n## Risks To Watch\n\n- Non-destructive fetch plus cursor pagination can still stall if one page repeatedly returns an undecryptable but valid envelope and the client never tombstones it. That is a separate correctness problem, not the response-growth problem `#67` is fixing.\n- Changing the fetch API requires coordinated node/client updates. Backward compatibility should be considered if mixed-version deployments matter.\n- Stable ordering must be server-owned. Sender-provided timestamps are attacker-controlled and should not drive pagination.\n\nIf this plan looks right, I’ll branch off fresh `origin/master` in an isolated workspace and execute it there.\n\n<oai-mem-citation>\n<citation_entries>\nMEMORY.md:35-35|note=[used general reminder to avoid generic fixes without grounding in repo evidence]\n</citation_entries>\n<rollout_ids>\n</rollout_ids>\n</oai-mem-citation>",
